header.gameNote: COLONIAL ATHLETIC ASSN TR AT RICHMOND VA

article.headline: Georgia St 72, Towson 64
article.story: RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Boyd Copeland scored all 10 of his points in the second half Friday, helping 10th-seeded Georgia State beat Towson 72-64 in the first round of the Colonial Athletic Association tournament. The Panthers (7-21) ended a seven-game losing streak and will face second-seeded league co-champion George Mason in the quarterfinals Saturday. Towson finished 12-16. Herman Favors hit all five of his first half 3-point shots and scored 16 points as the Panthers led 38-29 the break. Georgia State took a 14-point lead with 12:55 remaining when Lance Perique's two free throws moved the margin to 53-39. The Tigers rallied to within 64-61 on a pair of free throws by Lawrence Hamm, but Copeland's jumper and a pair of free throws by Favors with 1:01 left made it 68-61. Towson could get no closer than six in the final minute. Favors finished with 20 points, Malcolm Manier had 11 and Deven Dickerson and Copeland had 10 each. Hamm led the Tigers with 22 points and 14 rebounds. Dennard Abraham scored 18, and Gary Neal had 10.
